This research project investigated the impact of varying visual contrast of lightness and hue in cartographic symbolization on geospatial mental rotation tasks. &#8203;The study utilized behavioral experiments and fMRI neuroimaging methodologies to explore how different levels of visual contrast affect individuals' ability to perform map mental rotation tasks and identified associated brain activation patterns. &#8203; The outcomes of the project confirmed that visual contrast significantly influences a map reader's ability to make spatial judgments, impacting response time and accuracy. &#8203; The research emphasized the importance of considering both hue and lightness contrast together in map design to enhance user performance and map legibility. &#8203; The project's findings contribute to advancing knowledge in the fields of cartography and cognitive neuroscience, paving the way for future investigations into the complex interplay between visual contrast, brain activation, and map reading performance. &#8203;


The project outcomes have implications for understanding how individuals with different levels of geographical knowledge process spatial information, which can inform educational practices and cognitive research. &#8203; By identifying the impact of visual contrast on geospatial mental rotation tasks, the research provides insights into how map design can be optimized to enhance user experience and cognitive processing. &#8203; The findings also contribute to the broader field of cognitive neuroscience by elucidating the neural mechanisms involved in geospatial cognition tasks. &#8203; The interdisciplinary collaboration between cartography, psychology, and neuroscience showcased in the project highlights the value of combining different scientific approaches to gain a comprehensive understanding of complex cognitive processes. &#8203;


By investigating how visual contrast affects geospatial mental rotation tasks, this research underscores the importance of considering diverse user needs and cognitive abilities in map design. &#8203; This emphasis on inclusivity can lead to the development of more accessible and user-friendly cartographic products that cater to a wider range of individuals. Additionally, the project outcomes have the potential to inform policy decisions related to spatial cognition and map design, influencing practices in fields such as education, urban planning, and environmental management.


In summary, this research project has significantly advanced knowledge in the fields of cartography, cognitive neuroscience, and psychology by elucidating the role of visual contrast in geospatial mental rotation tasks.&#8203; The findings have practical implications for improving map design, enhancing spatial cognition skills, and promoting interdisciplinary collaboration in scientific research. &#8203;					Last Modified: 08/15/2024

